segments.text: You remember those, but normally there's plenty.
And I would say that the fact that they took us to church, or we went to church, and to the Young People's Union, kept us
on a straight and narrow, I guess.
And of course we had strong fest.
We had one family, the Lairds, they had a piano.
And of course one of my classmates, Edmund Laird, could play the piano.
I mean very good.
So everybody would go down there, all the teenagers would go down to their house and sing.
Now you really, I don't know why we didn't get in trouble, but we never did.
Let's talk about your education.
You went to Reagan High School in 1922 to 1926.
Before that time you were in Reagan Elementary Schools.
What were your favorite subjects?
Well, I didn't work real hard in school.
I played football, and I played basketball, and I played baseball, because you had to.
I had ten classmates in my high school, and about half of them were girls, so if you didn't play you didn't have a team.
As far as school is concerned, I think we had
we got as good an education as you can get in a small school.
And I think we probably got a better education than you get in the bigger school, large consolidated schools now.
Because you just got a lot of individual attention with only 11, 12, or 15 kids in each class.
Everybody took exactly the same.
the things you remember are not how hard you studied.
There's normally one teacher, Mrs. Young, when I was in the second grade while she was teaching me penmanship.
You know you're supposed to keep your wrist flat to the top of the desk and of course I was having problems so she was, she was getting all her long fingernails that pinched me on my
through my wrist and you remember those type of things.
But I guess that teaches you a lesson on penmanship.
But as far as, well of course my favorite subject was math because I didn't have to study.
It just came natural.
It just came natural that I could make a hundred on math almost without any problem, without even studying at all.

And you really don't study very much in a rural community where you go home and have to pick cotton after school and on Saturdays and bale hay and do all of that activity while you really don't have a lot of opportunity to study.
And I think the other...
Well, I think that as far as English is concerned in high school, it wasn't stressed enough in my high school.
It was not?
I can remember one teacher, why she liked to read, so instead of making us write themes and things of this sort, why she was reading some American literature or English literature,
And of course, at that age, well, you really don't pay much attention.
Right, right.
What do teachers think of you as a student?
Well, probably a dreamer.
What do you mean by that?
Well, I mean, you're always looking out the window and wanting to be outside rather than inside, that type of thing.
At least that's what they say.
And I don't know exactly what type of grade I had in high school.
I would say that I was making A's or 100's in mathematics and physics and this type of thing.
I was probably making in Spanish and Latin and all those.
I was probably just passing.
What about your popularity?
Would you consider yourself popular in high school?
Well, Stevenson, I guess everybody was popular.
I don't know.
Well, did they like you?
I guess that's what I mean.
Did you feel that your other student colleagues liked you?
Well, I don't know.
I don't think you ever get impressed as to whether or not they like you or not.
I had Debbie Harlan, who was a real good friend.
we really piled around together all the time.
And as far as getting in fights, you very seldom get in a squabble with anybody or things of this sort.
Okay.
Now you became a leader in the military.
Were you a
in any way a leader of any groups or organizations or maybe your baseball club or anything when you were in high school?
I mean did this leadership ability develop at this age or later?
Well, I don't know whether how it really develops.
It's real difficult to determine how you develop leadership or I think your
Compassion is developed during your high school years and your work years.
I think the way that your mother and dad handles you as far as giving you responsibilities and put you out on a cotton patch and go off and leave you and expect you to do your job, and you do it.
I think that being a leader on a football team, I don't think I was in the end.
So you really didn't, everybody played so I don't think it really had an effect on me.
When you graduated from high school,
At that time in your life, 17, 18 years old, did you have specific aims?
No, really I didn't.
I mean, I think I was just about like everybody else.
I was a lot of boys that really didn't know what they wanted to do.
And the only thing that I think that as far as everything along came to September, you were ready to go to school again.
You really didn't know what you wanted to do.
somebody from Tyler Commercial College had come around to the high schools, must have, and briefed you on.
I was going to ask you why you went there.
Well, I don't know how I got there.
But I'm quite sure that Mr. Roberts, who was president of Tyler Commercial College, must have either come around to the high school or sent you literature of some sort.
But anyway.
I got a hold of their name someplace.
Then I think I borrowed about $200 from the bank to pay the tuition and the board and room that was on Tyler Commercial College and I took off.
Well why did you think that obviously a commercial college is going to train you to become a businessman?
or something along that respect.
Why did you decide to go into a future of business instead of farming?
Well, as far as farming is concerned, it has so many ups and downs.
I mean, your drought, one year why we would have plenty of everything, and the next year
why even frost would destroy your plantings.
To me, it was a real frustrating type of business to be in.
And once you get into it, why, you're stuck in it.
I mean, it's really hard to get out of it.
Sure, but it also seems, from what you've been saying, that you had a real stable,
very stable economic base in your family.
Like you said, you were never hungry.
Well, you always had, Dad had big barns, and he would have hay that he kept over from year to year, and your corn cribs were filled, and they would be kept over from year to year.
And so, actually, it would kind of equalize it, but
Still, I figured working on a farm is a real hard job.
There should be some better way to make a living than that.
OK. At that age of 18, when you decided to go to Tyler Commercial College, were there any other alternatives besides either becoming a farmer or becoming a businessman?
Well, as far as I could see, that was the only alternative, as I said.
Okay, what did you think of Tyler Commercial College?
What were your impressions?
Well, Tyler Commercial College was an extremely good college.
I tell you, instead of taking Greg's shorthand, I took some of their, I mean, they had developed a shorthand, which I thought was a mistake that they were, I think it was called a burn shorthand.
But I learned...
bookkeeping there, and I learned typing there, and then you learned business letters, and it was a private secretarial course is what I really took.
Not that I had any idea at that time that that was my ultimate, you know.
It was the beginning then of what would culminate in your MBA.
Yeah, probably has.
The MBA is, we can talk about that probably a little later.
Yeah, we will.
And I had some time.
Were you interested in these business courses?
Oh, yeah.
Did they spark your imagination?
Oh, well, no, it was, well, I worked real,
I would say I worked, probably in high school, when you're doing all of your athletic activities and that type of thing, you really don't study very much.
And I would say I started studying a little bit when I was in Tyler Commercial College.
Why is that?
Well, you didn't have your outside activities.
You didn't have your athletics and things of that sort.
It was just going to school.
and we were living in a rooming house and there wasn't really a lot to do there.
And you went to church and to school and that was it.
How'd you do?
Well, I did pretty good.
I got a job before I graduated from the Lawrence Groceries Company.
What grocery company was that?
Lawrence Groceries Company in Bryan, Texas.
And with the proviso, if I kept the job down there, they'd send me a graduating certificate later on.
And it must have been around two or three weeks before I was scheduled to graduate that I went down to Tyler, down to the law school.
So Tyler let you out two or three weeks early to take this job, and then if you maintained the job,
why then they would send me my certificate later.
I see.
Did they?
Did they send you?
Oh yeah.
Oh yeah.
Well see the Lawrence Grocery Company is, was a company that had hired a number of graduates from Tyler Commercial College before.
So they had, they knew about Tyler Commercial College so they accepted their recommendation.
And then of course
after leaving Tyler Commercial College, getting to work at Lawrence Grocery Company, while Mr. Lawrence, John M. Lawrence, was a real fine individual.
I'd say he is one of two individuals outside of my parents who really influenced me a lot.
I mean, he was very considerate and

paid me well as far as I was concerned at the time, even though it was $75 a month, and was very fair, very small organization, and he was very generous as far as permitting me later on to, see he suggested that I apply for a poem at the West Point.
I mean really I got the name from him because he at one time applied for an appointment at West Point and couldn't get an appointment.
So he was very instrumental in suggesting that I apply for an appointment at West Point and he got the ball rolling.
This seems rather unusual that here you are in Bryan, Texas right next to Texas A&M.
And this man is thinking that you should go to West Point instead of Texas A&M.
Did he also suggest that you should start at Texas A&M?
No.
Why did you start at Texas A&M?
Well, I worked with Lawrenceville Grocery Company for about 18 months.
And I decided to...
Well, $75 a month, I saved enough money out of that $75 to pay my $200 back to the bank.
And then he raised my pay to $100 a month.
And then I saved, in 18 months, I saved about $500, which is $200 to pay that off and about $300 to go to school.
And I decided, by the way,
you may not even get to West Point.
I mean, the idea that he suggested it, and I worked at it, but I decided I'd better get going.
At that time, after working about a year and a half out of Tyler Commercial College, I decided that I was going to have to get an education of some sort.
Why'd you decide that?
Well, I don't know.
You know, you don't know why you decide to.
Not very many people back in 1926, 1927 were going to college.
And Harry, here you come up with this idea that you have to get an education.
Well, there were a lot of people at Texas A&M then.
I don't know how many people were in the school, but
I just couldn't see being an assistant bookkeeper and a billing clerk all your life.
If I'd stayed at Lawrence Grocery Company, I'd probably owned the place at some time later time.
But at that time, I was getting to the point where I was in a hurry, I guess.
Would you have considered yourself ambitious?
Well, I don't know.
You don't think of yourself as being ambitious.
trying to do at that time is decide what you want to do.

And I think after working at this grocery company of unloading, well, unloading boxcars full of sugar and flour and counting noses and doing all the billing and being assistant bookkeeper, why it appeared to you that
it would take you ten years or fifteen years or twenty years to ever become one of the salesmen.
So Mr. Lawrence, when I, well he was working on getting me an apartment in Westbourne.
What he did was really find out who had an apartment.
I mean he was on good terms with the various representatives from the area and also the
from Texas, and between he and W.S.
Barron.
Now W.S.
Barron was at that time a representative to the Texas legislature, and he was also a Sunday school teacher in the College Avenue Baptist Church.
Now the College Avenue Baptist Church is no longer, the name has
And that's where I attended.
So between the two of them, they gave me a lot of encouragement.
And then to get my poem at the West Point, I used, being a typist, I used to write letters of recommendation.
Well, Mr. Lawrence really found out that Tom Connolly, who was
was a representative from the 11th district, which was my home district, had an appointment.
And so then me, then I started flooding him with letters of recommendation.
I used to walk him down the streets of Bryan, Texas and get anybody to sign a letter of recommendation and mail it to him.
And I'd mail him probably three or four or five a week.
between those two individuals and I think it was Mrs. Pondexter who was the editor or the owner of the Bryan newspaper.
Those three individuals helped me out a lot.
And so I applied for the Department of the West part and I wasn't very confident that I was going to get it being
I think the first time Mr. Lawrence mentioned West Point I said, well where is that?
I wasn't very familiar with it.
So I worked on getting a part with West Point and I decided to quit and go to Texas A&M to work my way through school.
So I had my three hundred dollars.
So you had enough funds?
Well, I really didn't have enough funds.
I worked for Mr. Smith, who had a produce company, which was cleaning chickens.
You mean you quit Lawrence and went to work for Smith?
Well, it was a part-time.
See, for him, they gave me a room and board.
And I was
work the garden, drive Mrs. Smith wherever she wanted to go, wash the cars, keep them clean, wait on her table, and then on Saturdays I cleaned chickens in his produce place.
And I got my room and board.
And I attended Texas A&M as a day student.
Obviously you're on Bryan, but tell me some other reasons why you decided to go to Texas A&M.
Well, a number of my friends were going there who were also day students, and a guy named Black who had a vehicle and I could ride back and forth with him.
And you also could get in the Corps, and in fact almost everybody then was in the Corps.
Sure.
and you got paid some kind of allowance from the Army for being in the Corps and being in ROTC.
So anyway, any way to make a dime, I was interested in it.
Did the military aspect of A&M have anything to do with your decision?
What were your thoughts as a young man on the military?
Well, I was after an education, really, and I went to West Point because it was free education.
I really wasn't thinking about You hadn't thought much about the military.
No, you really hadn't.
You had no contact with the military.
The only other thing, you joined the Corps because that was the thing to do, and also you got some kind of clothing allowance or something to do.
Did you think of any other alternatives?
You were a young man in search of an education, it seems to me.
Did you ever think of going to the University of Texas or going to Rice or any other institution in the state?
No, the only other ones that I was interested in attending was Naval Academy or Coast Guard Academy or any of the academies that paid you to go to school.
And I did apply to...
to all of those.
You did, really?
Oh, yeah.
And what was the outcome?
Well, the Naval Academy, I was approaching the age limit that I could get in there.
See, West Point I think is twenty-two or twenty-one, and I think that Naval Academy could be over twenty.
And then the Coast Guard Academy, why, well, I just
work on that too hard, because I don't know why.
I just got to the point where I had somebody, Tom Conley, who had an appointment at West Point, and I just concentrated on him.
Okay.
Now, tell me about your first impressions when you became a student at A&M.
Well, you really don't remember a lot about it.
And I thoroughly enjoyed all my courses there.
Of course, I can't remember of having a counselor say you could only take so many subjects.
I think you just walked in and said, I want this, this, this, and this.
And somebody told you that, well, you're going to have to take this course because your high school didn't teach it.
And therefore, you had to, it's a non-credit course.
So you just took it.
and bought your books and of course why I selected architecture I don't know.
That's a good question.
That was my next question.
You were interested in mathematics and you had some business background and then you decided to become an architect.
Any ideas on that?
I'm talented in that particular field.
I mean, just like getting in the housing business after retiring.
I think that the fact that I was interested in architecture and layout of buildings and construction of buildings is what I was really, really interested in at the time.
And so I really was thinking I was going to concentrate in the
get into the larger building type of thing.
And you can't remember too much about going to Texas A&M other than the fact that you work and you never did anything.
I never saw a football game, I never saw a movie, you never had a date unless it was
church or something in some place that didn't cost anything.
You were just working all the time then?
Yeah, well I got down to oh about $165 during that year and then Lawrence Closet got me, gave me a bonus of $50.
See I'd worked for them half a year so at Christmas time they gave me
gave me a bonus of $50, which, well, that was about a million dollars at that time.
Sure, sure.
Because that really helped me, that really got me over the hump.
And then the last month that I was at Texas A&M, I had enough money to pay room and board, so I moved out of the Smith's house into a rooming house for the last
about last 30 days.
You were a day student, while most of the students at that time of course lived right in the dorms.
Did you have any problems with that?
Well, you probably didn't.
Being a day student probably took a lot away from the, a little away from the hazing that you got.
Sure.
Because you weren't in a position that they could
chase you out of the barracks in the middle of the night or go out and sleep in the haystacks and things of this sort.
But you got plenty of paddling.
And the fish year was, I'd say the fish year at Texas A&M is a lot worse than the cleave year at West Point.
Oh, it was.
Oh, yeah.
There's no question about it.
Because at West Point, they don't touch you, whereas at Texas A&M,
they pat you and at that time hate you pretty well.
What outfit in the corps were you in?
I think I was in engineers.
And I think all architectural students were in engineers and several engineering students and what have you.
I think that's the way it was divided, as I remember.
Did they have you in a special day student corps outfit?
No, I don't think so.
I don't remember really too much about it, but it seems to me that you always went to that particular barracks or whatever they call them, at that time.
where the headquarters were, and that's where you reported in.
Did you have to report in every morning?
I don't remember.
I don't think so.
I think you only reported in when you had drill or some military subject that you had to take.
You were only in the Corps for one year.
What were your colleagues like?
Well, real, I mean, as far as I was concerned, the people who were in the architecture were, I mean, they were all real fine individuals.
I mean, all of them had the same problem as I. I would say that there's, we wrote back and forth, I read four or five day students from Brian, but your, the youngsters who worked on
who lived on campus, well I don't, you don't remember a lot of, there's no carousing, no drinking, no dope, no, everybody that would seem to be was there for an education.
And they worked, and everybody worked hard.
